l interpretations of each of the plays, Craig discusses the demise of divine right inRichard II, political upheaval and disputed rule in Henry IV, Parts 1 and 2, and the attempt to reestablish legitimacy on a new basis in Henry V. While focusing especially on the plays' various interpretive puzzles,Craig shows how the four plays constitute one narrative, culminating in the rule of England's most famous warrior king, Henry V, whose brilliant achievements were undone by ill fortune. Craig concludes with an epilogue on what might have been had Henry lived to consolidate his conquest of France and unify it with England under a single crown. Supported by a wealth of scholarship, both historical and critical, The Philosopher's English King makes a major contribution to the burgeoning scholarship on Shakespeare as a political thinker, providing further evidence for why the poet deserves to be recognized as a philosopher in his own right. Leon Harold Craig is professor emeritus of political science at the University of Alberta.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHistorical drama, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aKings and rulers in literature. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aBritish History.  aBritish Monarchy.  aDivine right.  aEngland.  aHenriad.  aHenry V.  aLegitimacy.  aPolitical Authority.  aPolitical Philosophy.  aPolitical authority.  aPolitical philosophy.  aPolitical thinker.  aShakespeare.  aShakespearean Politics.  aShakespearean Studies.  aWarrior king.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/